article.description:
Raef LaFrentz had six 3-pointers among his 30 points, and Dirk Nowitzki scored 14 of his 30 points early in the third quarter as the Dallas Mavericks beat the Golden State
Warriors 117-100 Saturday night.
article.headline: Warriors lose 12th straight time to Mavs
article.linkText: LaFrentz, Nowitzki score 30 each as Mavs top Warriors
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Raef LaFrentz plans to take advantage of all the opportunities and options presented to the Dallas Mavericks' big men.
LaFrentz

LaFrentz had six 3-pointers among his 30 points, and Dirk Nowitzki scored 14 of his 30 points early in the third quarter as the Mavericks beat the Golden State Warriors 117-100 Saturday night. LaFrentz, in his most impressive game since joining the Mavericks in a trade on Feb. 21, went 12-for-19 from the field before sitting out the fourth quarter. After Golden State hung with the Midwest Division leaders in the first half, Dallas' inside-outside versatility and full-throttle pace exhausted the Warriors in the third. LaFrentz made the most of his many wide-open shots. "My release felt good, and my shot was going down, and my teammates got me the ball where I could do something with it," LaFrentz said. "This is a unique team, because our small (guys) are the ones posting up, and our big (guys) are the ones spotting up for the 3s. Whatever works to get us the win, I guess." Michael Finley added 27 points for Dallas, which beat Golden State for the 12th straight time. The Mavericks broke open a close game in the third quarter with a blistering 21-8 run befitting the NBA's highest-scoring team. With the enviable outside range displayed by big men Nowitzki and LaFrentz -- and the playmaking tenacity of Finley and Steve Nash -- it's easy to see why the Mavericks present more matchup problems for opponents than perhaps any other team. "When you play against that team, you know you're going to run up and down the court and get a lot of opportunities to score some points, but it's difficult to guard those guys," said Antawn Jamison, who had 20 points for Golden State. "You know it's going to be the type of pace you want to play at, but you're going to have your hands full." Dallas won for the sixth time in seven games to move a half-game behind Sacramento and the Los Angeles Lakers for first place in the Western Conference, but the Mavericks struggled to pull away from the last-place Warriors until the second half. "I was worried about this game all day long," Mavs coach Don Nelson said. "We've won here quite a lot ... but we took a while to figure out what we needed to do. It's not an ideal situation, but we know how to win in this building." Chris Mills scored 19 points in a reserve role among seven players in double figures for the Warriors, who lost their fifth straight. Golden State played without leading rebounder Danny Fortson, who served the first of a two-game suspension for accumulating too many flagrant foul points. Erick Dampier scored all 15 of his points in the first half for Golden State. Troy Murphy, who started alongside fellow rookies Gilbert Arenas and Jason Richardson, had 13 points. The Warriors had three rookies in their starting lineup for the first time since April 22, 1995, but Murphy was removed in favor of Mills in the third after Nowitzki hit several outside shots over him. "We came out flat in the first four minutes of the third quarter, and I have no idea why," Warriors coach Brian Winters said. Nash had seven points and nine assists for Dallas despite sitting out the entire second quarter. Greg Buckner had seven points and nine rebounds for the Mavericks. Game notes
The Warriors, who sold out their previous two home games against Sacramento and the Lakers, had more than 16,000 lively fans at The Arena in Oakland. ... Golden State has allowed more than 100 points in 15 of its last 17 games, while Dallas has scored more than 100 in 18 of its last 21. ... Fortson also will miss Golden State's home game against Washington on Monday night.
